#### Step 2: Recall Properties of Suprema

Recall that for any two real-valued functions `a(i)` and `b(i)`, we have:

`supᵢ (a(i) + b(i)) ≤ supᵢ a(i) + supᵢ b(i)`.

This is because:
1. For each `i`, `a(i) + b(i) ≤ supᵢ a(i) + supᵢ b(i)` because `a(i) ≤ supᵢ a(i)` and `b(i) ≤ supᵢ b(i)`.
2. Therefore, `supᵢ a(i) + supᵢ b(i)` is an upper bound for the set `{a(i) + b(i) | i ∈ ι}`.
3. By definition of supremum, `supᵢ (a(i) + b(i)) ≤ supᵢ a(i) + supᵢ b(i)`.

#### Step 3: Formalize the Supremum Property

We can directly apply the property of suprema to the functions `eLpNorm (X i) 2 P` and `eLpNorm (Y i) 2 P`. 

