### Solution

The key observation is that for any indexed family of real numbers `(a_i)` and `(b_i)`, we have 
`⨆ i, (a_i + b_i) ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)`.
This follows because for any fixed `i`, `a_i + b_i ≤ (⨆ i, a_i) + (⨆ i, b_i)`, and taking the supremum over `i` preserves the inequality.

In our case, we have `a_i = eLpNorm (X i) 2 P` and `b_i = eLpNorm (Y i) 2 P`. 

Here is the formal Lean proof:

